<chapter id="ch0041">
    <title>GRAM-POSITIVE RODS</title>
    <sect1 id="ch0041s0001">
      <title>GRAM-POSITIVE RODS</title>
      <anchor id="ch0041s0001a0001"/>
      <sect2 id="ch0041s0001s0001">
        <title>25 General Approaches to the Identification of Aerobic Gram-Positive Rods</title>
        <anchor id="ch0041s0001s0001a0001"/>
        <para role="chapterAuthor"><phrase role="center">KATHRYN A. BERNARD</phrase>
        </para>
        <para id="ch0041s0001s0001p0001">The purpose of this algorithm for the identification of aerobic (and some facultatively anaerobic) Gram-positive rods is to assist the reader in finding the appropriate chapter in this<emphasis>Manual</emphasis> for further information. This algorithm emphasizes that the Gram stain (performed on 24- to 48-h-old colonies from rich media) and documentation of macroscopic colony morphologies are critical features for the differentiation of these taxa. All strains of Gram-positive rods (except the non-rapidly growing mycobacteria) reviewed here can be initially grown on blood agar plates, with specific descriptions of growth requirements being discussed in individual chapters.</para>
        <para id="ch0041s0001s0001p0002">Gram-positive organisms demonstrating “regular” rods are those cells with usually parallel (not curved) longitudinal edges. If spore formation is not observed initially, spores can be tested for on a nutritionally depleted medium. “Irregular” rods are those organisms with cells observed to have curved or coccoidal longitudinal edges which are not parallel; these taxa can produce yellowish-, yellow-, or orange-pigmented colonies. Beta-hemolysis is best observed when cells are incubated in a CO<subscript>2</subscript>-enriched atmosphere. Some genera that stain partially acid-fast (e.g., <emphasis>Gordonia</emphasis> and <emphasis>Rhodococcus</emphasis>) may also show a yellow-orange pigment (<ulink url="ch0045#ch0045s0001">chapter 29</ulink>). Rods exhibiting vegetative substrate filaments may show branched-type hyphae, which either form spores or reproduce by fragmentation. Vegetative substrate filaments might not be present initially (i.e., within 48 h), and thus may be prone to being misidentified. Molecular methods may be required for definitive identification to genus and species level for bacteria which are poorly reactive biochemically and/or are underrepresented or absent from databases of commercial matrix-assisted laser desorption ionization–time-of-flight mass spectrometry (MALDI-TOF MS) systems. Genera that contain strictly anaerobic Gram-positive rods may also contain species, or strains within a species, that grow reasonably well in the presence of oxygen. This is particularly true for <emphasis>Actinomyces</emphasis>, the genera formerly <emphasis>Actinomyces, Actinobaculum, Actinotignum</emphasis>, some <emphasis>Propionibacterium/Cutibacterium</emphasis> spp. (<ulink url="ch0072#ch0072s0001">chapter 55</ulink>), and <emphasis>Clostridium tertium</emphasis> (a strong gas producer), as well as other aerotolerant <emphasis>Clostridium</emphasis> spp. (<ulink url="ch0073#ch0073s0001">chapter 56</ulink>). Some aerobic Gram-positive cocci, e.g., taxa assigned to the genus <emphasis>Leuconostoc</emphasis> spp. (<ulink url="ch0040#ch0040s0001">chapter 24</ulink>) and <emphasis>Streptococcus mutans</emphasis> (<ulink url="ch0038#ch0038s0001">chapter 22</ulink>), might be misidentified as Gram-positive rods because of their initial Gram stain appearance after growth on plate agar media rather than from a broth, where their appearance is coccoidal. Some Gram-positive rods (e.g., <emphasis>Rhodococcus</emphasis> spp. [<ulink url="ch0045#ch0045s0001">chapter 29</ulink>] or <emphasis>Dermabacter</emphasis> [<ulink url="ch0044#ch0044s0001">chapter 28</ulink>]) might be misidentified as Gram-positive cocci because of their initial Gram stain appearance. After preliminary examination of the pathogen, the microbiologist should refer to <anchor id="ch0041s0001s0001a0002"/><link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001a0005">Table 1</link>, where a wide variety of genera of Gram-positive rods are cross-referenced with respect to relevant chapters in this <emphasis>Manual</emphasis>.</para>
        <para id="ch0041s0001s0001p0003">Molecular approaches to characterize or subtype pathogens described in this section are described briefly in each chapter of this<emphasis>Manual</emphasis>, as well as in overviews in <ulink url="ch0023#ch0023s0001">chapters 8</ulink> and <ulink url="ch0027#ch0027s0001">12</ulink>. 16S rRNA gene and other (secondary) gene target sequencing methods have become established tools in many microbiology laboratories; these approaches are critical for definitive identification of bacteria which are not unambiguously identified by biochemical methods and are increasingly identified by the use of MALDI-TOF MS systems, because rare pathogens may be underrepresented or absent from commercial databases. Interpretation of sequence data must be done by personnel with a good working knowledge of current approaches for taxonomy and systematics. Instances exist where 16S rRNA gene sequence analysis cannot be used as the sole characterization method, particularly where a patient isolate has &gt;98.7% (<link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0001">1</link>) or 99% (<link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0002">2</link>) identity to sequences from type strains of two or more validly described species. In such cases, sequencing of secondary or additional gene targets is recommended (<link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0002">2</link>).</para>
        <para id="ch0041s0001s0001p0004">MALDI-TOF MS technology is now widely used in clinical microbiology, because that method has been consistently found to provide rapid, cost-effective, and accurate identifications of both common and rare pathogens (<ulink url="ch0020#ch0020s0001">chapter 5</ulink>). Applications and limitations for this technology are outlined for individual taxa described in each chapter; several reviews of MALDI-TOF MS applications are provided below in references <link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0003">3</link> through <link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0005">5</link>.</para>
        <para id="ch0041s0001s0001p0005">The use of whole-genome sequencing of bacterial genomes has progressed rapidly since the last edition of this<emphasis>Manual</emphasis>. Draft or closed genomes for many of the clinically relevant Gram-positive taxa outlined in the bacteriology chapters of this <emphasis>Manual</emphasis> have now been deposited into the public databases at the NCBI or described in peer-reviewed publications. The performance of whole-genome sequencing has decreased considerably in cost over recent years, and thus may prove to be an attractive method for characterizing taxa in the near future, combining identification and strain typing with detection of resistance genes and resolution of virulence factors in one step (<link linkend="ch0041s0001s0001s0001li0006">6</link>).</para>
